Aegnor	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Fourth son of Finarfin and Eärwen, and younger brother of Finrod Felagund, Angrod, and Galadriel. In Beleriand, he and his brother Angrod held the highlands of Dorthonion as vassals of their elder brother Finrod. A prince of the House of Finarfin, he belonged to one of the chief Noldorin lines active in the wars and realms of the First Age.
Aiwendil	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia associated with the Valië Yavanna, the Queen of Earth, possessing a strong affinity for animals and growing things. Chosen by Yavanna, he was later sent to Middle-earth as one of the Istari in the Third Age. His name in the original tongue relates to his connection with nature, and in later ages he became known for his love of beasts and birds above the concerns of Elves and Men.
Alatar	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of Oromë the Huntsman, chosen by his lord to be sent to Middle-earth as one of the Istari. He took his friend Pallando with him on this mission, and the two were known collectively as the Blue Wizards or Ithryn Luin. Their work was associated with the far East and South of Middle-earth. In some accounts Alatar is also called Morinehtar, meaning Darkness-slayer.
Amras	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The younger of the twin sons of Fëanor and Nerdanel, and the youngest of their seven children born in Valinor during the days of the Two Trees. Red-haired like his twin brother Amrod, he was alike with him in mood and face, though twins were very rare among the Eldar. He and Amrod were known as hunters and are usually remembered together among the sons of Fëanor.
Amrod	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The elder of the twin sons of Fëanor and Nerdanel, and the sixth of their seven children. Red-haired, though his hair grew darker than that of his twin Amras, he was alike with his brother in mood and face, and twins were very rare among the Eldar. He and Amras were known as hunters and are among the least separately described of the princes of the Noldor.
Amárië	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Vanyar">Vanyar</a><br><br>A Vanyarin Elf beloved by Finrod Felagund. Though they loved one another, they did not wed, and when Finrod joined the Exile of the Noldor, Amárië did not follow him to Beleriand. According to some accounts, she was not permitted to accompany him. She remained in Valinor, linking her story to the separation between the Vanyar of Aman and the Noldorin exiles.
Anairë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Wife of Fingolfin and mother of four children: Fingon, Turgon, Aredhel, and Argon. She was a Noldo whose name means Holiest in Quenya. Little is told of her, except that she did not leave Aman, largely because of her close friendship with Eärwen, wife of Finarfin.
Angrod	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Third son of Finarfin and Eärwen, brother to Finrod Felagund, Aegnor, and Galadriel, and father of Orodreth. In Beleriand, he and his younger brother Aegnor ruled over Dorthonion as vassals of their elder brother Finrod, holding the highlands during the Siege of Angband. He belonged to the House of Finarfin and to the Noldorin leadership of the northern marches.
Aredhel	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The White Lady of the Noldor, also called Ar-Feiniel, third child and only daughter of Fingolfin and Anairë. Her brothers were Fingon, Turgon, and Argon. Tall and strong, she was fond of hunting and riding in the forests, with pale skin, dark hair, and garments of silver and white. She dwelt in Gondolin with her brother Turgon but longed for wider lands, and her story is closely tied to Nan Elmoth, Eöl the Dark Elf, and her son Maeglin.
Argon	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Argon was the fourth and last child of Fingolfin and Anairë, and the youngest son of Fingolfin. His elder brothers were Fingon and Turgon, and his sister was Aredhel. His Quenya name was Arakáno, meaning High Commander, a name connected with his impetuous character.
Arien	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia associated with fire and with the Sun. In the days of the Two Trees, she served in the gardens of Vána, tending the golden flowers and watering them with dew gathered from Laurelin. Melkor failed to corrupt her, and the Valar chose her to guide the vessel of the Sun through the airs of Arda. Her Quenya name means Maiden of Sun.
Arminas	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin Elf, one of Angrod's people, who later dwelt among the followers of Círdan the Shipwright. He travelled with his companion Gelmir as a messenger of Círdan, and the two encountered Tuor near Annon-in-Gelydh, the Gate of the Noldor. Their eyes marked them as Calaquendi born in Valinor before the Exile. Arminas is a Sindarin name meaning Royal Tower.
Aulë|Mahal	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>One of the Aratar, the smith and master of crafts among the Valar, and third most powerful among them. He governs the substances of the earth and delights in works of craft, from small works to the forging of lands, mountains, rocks, gems, and minerals. Husband to Yavanna, he dwells with her in central Valinor. The Dwarves call him Mahal, the Maker, and the Noldor became his students and friends in Valinor; among the Maiar associated with him were Curumo and Mairon.
Beleg	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>Beleg Cúthalion, meaning Strongbow, was a Sinda who served King Elu Thingol of Doriath. Together with Mablung, he was one of the great captains of the Sindar and served as captain of the Marchwardens on Doriath's northern borders. He was considered the best archer and huntsman of his time, carrying the black bow Belthronding and the arrow Dailir. Beleg became a friend and brother-in-arms of Túrin, and was known for loyalty, skill in battle, and compassion.
Caranthir	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>One of the Sons of Fëanor, known as Caranthir the Dark. Among his brothers he was the harshest and quickest to anger. His father-name was Morifinwë, meaning Dark Finwë, for he was black-haired like his paternal grandfather, while his mother-name Carnistir referred to his ruddy complexion. His realm was in Thargelion in eastern Beleriand, where his people had much contact and trade with the Dwarves of the Blue Mountains.
Celeborn	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>One of the noblest of the Sindar, a prince of Doriath and kinsman of King Thingol. In one genealogy he was the grandson of Elmo, Thingol's brother, and therefore belonged to the royal kindred of the Sindar. In Doriath he met Galadriel of the House of Finarfin, and the two were joined in love. His Sindarin name means Silver-tall or Silver Tree, from elements connected with silver and height.
Celebrimbor	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Son of Curufin, greatest of the craftsmen of Eregion and lord of the Gwaith-i-Mírdain, the People of the Jewel-smiths. As a craftsman he was second only to Fëanor his grandfather, surpassing in cunning all others who have ever wrought save Fëanor alone. In the Second Age he forged the Rings of Power in Eregion, and the Three Rings of the Elves, Vilya, Narya, and Nenya, were his own work and untouched by Sauron.
Celegorm	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin prince and the third of the seven sons of Fëanor and Nerdanel. He was a great huntsman and a friend of the Vala Oromë, from whom he learned great skill with birds and beasts and the understanding of many of their languages. Oromë gave him the great hound Huan. Celegorm was often in the company of his brother Curufin, and the two held and fortified Himlad, including the Pass of Aglon.
Curufin	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin prince, the fifth son of Fëanor and Nerdanel, and Fëanor's favorite son. He resembled his father greatly in skill, temperament, and appearance, and was the chief inheritor among his brothers of Fëanor's mastery in craftsmanship. Curufin was the father of Celebrimbor, swore the Oath of Fëanor with his brothers, and held Himlad alongside Celegorm, with whom he was closely associated.
Curumo	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of Aulë the Smith, from whom he acquired great knowledge of smithing and handiwork. Chosen by Aulë to be sent to Middle-earth as chief of the Istari. His name in Quenya relates to his skill in craft and devices. At Yavanna's request, he took Aiwendil with him on the mission to Middle-earth in the Third Age.
Círdan	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Teleri">Teleri</a><br><br>The Shipwright, whose name means shipmaker in Sindarin, and one of the oldest and wisest of the Elves in Middle-earth. Born Nōwē and kin to both Elwë and Olwë, the kings of the Teleri, he remained in Middle-earth when his kindred departed for Valinor. He became Lord of the Falathrim, established the Havens of Brithombar and Eglarest, and was a master shipbuilder taught by Ossë. In later ages he was associated with the Grey Havens in Lindon and with the keeping of Narya, the Ring of Fire.
Daeron	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>A Sindarin Elf who dwelt in Doriath as the chief loremaster and minstrel of King Thingol during the First Age. He was regarded among the greatest musicians of the Elves, with Maglor named in similar esteem. Daeron devised the Cirth, the runes that were little used among the Sindar except in Menegroth, where the Dwarves learned them and later carried them east over the Blue Mountains. He loved Lúthien, daughter of Thingol and Melian, though his love was not returned.
Dior	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Dior Eluchíl, meaning Thingol's Heir, was the son of Beren Erchamion and Lúthien Tinúviel, and first of the Peredhil. Through his parents he was of threefold descent: from the Edain through Beren, the Eldar through Thingol, and the Maiar through Melian. Called Dior Aranel the Beautiful, he wedded Nimloth of Doriath and had three children: Eluréd, Elurín, and Elwing. He became closely associated with Menegroth and the royal inheritance of Doriath.
Ecthelion	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Ecthelion of the Fountain was an Elf-lord of Gondolin and captain of the House of the Fountain, one of the twelve houses of the Gondothlim. He possessed the most beautiful voice and greatest musical talent with the flute among all the people of the hidden city. His house and title connect him with the Fountain of the King and the noble martial traditions of Gondolin.
Egalmoth	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Gnome-lord of Gondolin in the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales. He was leader of the folk of the Heavenly Arch, wore a blue mantle embroidered with stars of crystal, and carried a bent sword, unlike the other Noldoli. Though armed with that sword, he trusted especially to his bow and could shoot farther than anyone of his folk.
Eldalótë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The wife of Angrod and mother of Orodreth, a lord of Nargothrond. She probably joined the Exile of the Noldor, since her name was translated into Sindarin in later legend, though she is not mentioned in the tales of Beleriand. Her Quenya name means Elven-flower, from Elda meaning Elf and lótë meaning flower, and its Sindarin form was Edhellos.
Elendil	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Men">Men</a><br><br>Elendil the Tall was a Númenórean lord of the Faithful, the son of Amandil and the father of Isildur and Anárion. He was founder and first High King of the Realms in Exile, ruling over Arnor in the north and Gondor in the south. Remembered among the Dúnedain as a wise king and heroic figure, he was also notable for his great height. His Quenya name means Lover of the Stars, and among the Edain it also carried the meaning Elf-friend.
Elenwë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Vanyar">Vanyar</a><br><br>Wife of Turgon and mother of Idril Celebrindal. One of the Vanyar, her golden hair passed to her daughter. She is remembered as the only known full Vanya who accompanied the Flight of the Noldor, linking the usually Aman-dwelling Vanyar to the story of Turgon and Idril.
Elmo	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>An Elf of the royal house of the Teleri, younger brother of Elwë and Olwë. Born during the Great Journey, he remained in Beleriand and stayed close to Elwë, by whom he was beloved. Elmo is not associated with recorded deeds of his own, but he stands within the royal kindred of the Sindar and is important to the genealogy of Doriath through his descendants Celeborn and Nimloth.
Elrond	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Son of Eärendil the Mariner and Elwing the White, twin brother of Elros, and bearer of the Elven-ring Vilya. Born at the Havens of Sirion, he was one of the Half-elven and chose to be counted among the Elves. In the Second Age he established the refuge of Imladris, called Rivendell, where he dwelt as lord and master. Father of Arwen Undómiel, he was renowned for wisdom, healing, and knowledge of ancient lore.
Elros	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Elros Tar-Minyatur, son of Eärendil the Mariner and Elwing, and twin brother of Elrond. Born at the Havens of Sirion, he was one of the Half-elven and chose to be counted among Men. He became the first King of Númenor, taking the royal name Tar-Minyatur in Quenya, meaning High First-ruler, and from him came the Line of Elros, the royal house of Númenor.
Elwing	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Elwing the White, daughter of Dior Eluchíl and Nimloth of Doriath, and wife of Eärendil the Mariner. She had two elder twin brothers, Eluréd and Elurín, and was the mother of the twin sons Elrond and Elros. Through her descent from Beren and Lúthien, Thingol, and Melian, she belonged to the mingled lines of Men, Elves, and Maiar. When the Valar offered the Half-elven their choice, she chose to be counted among the Elves.
Eru Ilúvatar|Ilúvatar|Eru	The transcendent creator who exists eternally in the Timeless Halls beyond the world and bears the Flame Imperishable, the power by which true life is kindled. From his thought he brought forth the Ainur, and to teach them he set before them his theme in the form of music; as they learned to sing together, the Great Music unfolded. Out of that Music he revealed a Vision of the world and its history, and then he spoke the word “Eä,” giving being to the universe itself. Many of the Ainur entered Eä and became the Valar and the Maiar, shaping Arda according to the design shown in the Vision, while Ilúvatar remained beyond the world yet loved it and set its laws and bounds. When discord arose in the Music, he introduced new themes that could not be quenched and declared that no theme can be played that does not have its source in him, so even rebellion would be woven into a greater harmony. He is called Eru, “He that is Alone,” and Ilúvatar, “Father of All,” and the Children of Ilúvatar are the Elves and Men, the Firstborn and the Secondborn. He rarely intervenes directly, but life and fate are ultimately his gift and his design stands above all.
Estë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>One of the Valier and the wife of Irmo, dwelling with him in the Gardens of Lórien. She had the power to heal all hurts and weariness, was always clad in grey, and favored an island on the tree-shadowed lake of Lórellin where she slept during the day. In Lórien, Estë and Irmo tended to the Elves of Valinor, who drew refreshment from the fountains, and even the Valar came there for repose and ease from the burdens of Arda.
Eärendil	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Half-elven">Half-elven</a><br><br>Eärendil the Mariner was one of the Half-elven, the son of Tuor and Idril, daughter of King Turgon. Raised in Gondolin during the First Age, he later lived in Arvernien by the Havens of Sirion, where he became leader of the people there. He married Elwing, daughter of Dior and descendant of Beren and Lúthien, and their sons were Elrond and Elros. With the aid of Círdan the Shipwright, Eärendil built the ship Vingilótë and was remembered as a mariner of great importance in the legends of the Elder Days.
Eärwen	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Teleri">Teleri</a><br><br>The Swan-maiden of Alqualondë, daughter of Olwë, lord of the Teleri in Aman. Wife of Finarfin and mother of Finrod, Angrod, Aegnor, and Galadriel. Her children, being in part Sea-elves through their mother, had a love of the sea and longing for distant places, and it was partly due to this inheritance that all four chose to join the exile to Middle-earth, though Eärwen herself remained in Aman. Because of their Telerin blood through Eärwen, her children were well received in Doriath, the realm of her father's elder brother Thingol. Her name means Sea-maiden.
Eöl	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>Known as the Dark Elf, Eöl was a great smith who dwelt alone in the forest of Nan Elmoth in East Beleriand. Akin to Thingol and a friend of the Dwarves of Nogrod and Belegost, he learned much of their craft. He devised galvorn, a black metal of great strength and malleability, and forged the swords Anglachel and Anguirel from the iron of a fallen meteorite. His story is closely bound to Aredhel of the Noldor and their son Maeglin.
Eönwë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>The banner-bearer and herald of Manwë, and chief of the Maiar along with Ilmarë. He served as Manwë's messenger and representative in matters of great authority, and his role connects him closely with the power and judgment of the Elder King. His name is Quenya in form, though the ancient Loremasters knew no Elvish etymology for it and considered it probably Valarin in origin.
Finarfin	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Youngest son of Finwë and his second wife Indis of the Vanyar. Husband of Eärwen daughter of Olwë, and father of Finrod, Angrod, Aegnor, and Galadriel. During the Flight of the Noldor he turned back to Valinor with a portion of his people and was afterward reckoned King of the Noldor who remained in Aman. Through Eärwen, his house had close kinship with the Teleri and with Thingol of Doriath.
Findis	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin Elf, the first child and daughter of Finwë, King of the Noldor, and Indis, his second wife. She did not follow the Noldor into exile, instead abiding among the Vanyar with her mother. Her name was a combination of the names of her parents.
Finduilas	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin princess of the First Age, daughter of Orodreth, ruler of Nargothrond, and sister of Gil-galad. She lived in Nargothrond under the rule of Finrod Felagund and was betrothed to Gwindor. He gave her the Sindarin name Faelivrin, meaning Gleam of the Sun on the Pools of Ivrin.
Fingolfin	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Second son of Finwë, born of his second wife Indis of the Vanyar, making him half-Vanyarin. Strongest and most valiant of the sons of Finwë, he became High King of the Noldor in Middle-earth. Husband of Anairë and father of Fingon, Turgon, Aredhel, and Argon, he led his people across the Helcaraxë and later helped maintain the Siege of Angband against Morgoth.
Fingon	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Eldest son of Fingolfin and Anairë, and later High King of the Noldor. He was renowned for his daring rescue of Maedhros, his cousin and friend, from Thangorodrim. Aided by Thorondor, the King of Eagles, Fingon freed Maedhros, and the deed helped heal the breach between the Houses of Fingolfin and Fëanor.
Finrod	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Eldest son of Finarfin and Eärwen, called Felagund by the Dwarves, meaning Maker of Caves. Wise, just, and powerful, he was the greatest traveler among the Eldar. He established the stronghold of Nargothrond in the Caverns of Narog, first encountered Men among Bëor's people in Ossiriand, and became a teacher and friend to the Edain, who called him Nóm, meaning Wisdom. Fairest and most beloved of the House of Finwë, he was known for loyalty, music, and friendship.
Finwë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>First King of the Noldor and founder of the House of Finwë, from which branched the houses of Fëanor, Fingolfin, and Finarfin. He led his people on the Great Journey from Cuiviénen to Valinor and established the city of Tirion upon Túna in Eldamar. His first wife was Míriel, mother of Fëanor, and his second wife was Indis of the Vanyar, mother of Fingolfin and Finarfin.
Fëanor	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Eldest and most beloved son of Finwë, King of the Noldor. Greatest of the Noldor in skill of word and hand, he was renowned as a craftsman, gem-smith, and warrior. His mother Míriel named him Fëanáro, meaning Spirit of Fire. His most famous work was the creation of the Silmarils, three jewels that captured the light of the Two Trees of Valinor. He was father of seven sons and became one of the central figures among the princes of the Noldor.
Galadhon	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>A noble Elf of Doriath, son of Elmo and therefore nephew of King Thingol and Olwë. Little is known of Galadhon himself beyond his place in the royal kindred of the Teleri and his children: Celeborn and Galathil. His name is Sindarin and appears to combine galadh, meaning tree, with the masculine suffix -on.
Galadriel	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Daughter of Finarfin and Eärwen, and younger sister to Finrod Felagund, Angrod, and Aegnor. Received two names according to Eldar custom: her father named her Artanis meaning Noblewoman, and her mother named her Nerwen. Born in Aman as one of the Noldor, she took part in the Exile following Fëanor's rebellion. Mightiest and fairest of all the Elves that remained in Middle-earth. With her husband Celeborn, she ruled over the woodland realm of Lothlórien in later ages. Her Telerin heritage through her mother Eärwen allowed her to be well received in Doriath by her kinsman Thingol.
Galathil	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>A Sindarin Elf of the royal kindred of Doriath, grandson of Elmo and brother of Celeborn, Lord of Lórien. His daughter Nimloth wedded Dior, Thingol's Heir, making Galathil a distant ancestor of both Elrond and Aragorn. His name belongs to a group of names shared by his close kin and connected with the White Trees.
Galdor	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Gnome-lord of Gondolin in the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales. He was lord of the folk of the Tree, who wore green and probably carried either great clubs or spears. Galdor was said to be the bravest of the Gondothlim after King Turgon himself, and his name is associated with roots related to thriving and trees.
Gelmir	See <a href="bword://disambiguation.stardict?Gelmir">disambiguation page</a>.
Gelmir (messenger of Círdan)	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin Elf, originally one of Angrod's people, who later settled among the folk of Círdan the Shipwright in the southern regions of Beleriand. He was sent by Círdan as a messenger together with Arminas, bearing a warning from Ulmo. During their journey they encountered Tuor at the Gate of the Noldor and aided him on his path. Both Gelmir and Arminas were Calaquendi, born in Valinor before the Exile.
Gelmir (son of Guilin)	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A noble Elf of Nargothrond, son of Guilin and brother of Gwindor. He is chiefly remembered in connection with his brother and the great wars of Beleriand. His Sindarin name is of unclear meaning, though it could combine gell, meaning joy, and mîr, meaning jewel.
Gil-galad	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>High King of the Noldor in Middle-earth during the Second Age, ruling longer than any of his predecessors. He founded a kingdom in Lindon in the far northwest of Middle-earth and was acknowledged as High King of the Elves of the West. A major ruler among the Eldar, he was closely associated with Lindon, the Elves of the West, and the great alliances of the Second Age.
Glorfindel|Glorifindel	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A noble Elf-lord of Gondolin and chief of the House of the Golden Flower, one of the mightiest warriors of the Noldor. His house bore the device of a rayed sun upon their shields, and he wore a mantle embroidered with celandines in golden threads, with arms damascened in gold. Renowned for courage and nobility, his name and house were remembered in song among the great traditions of Gondolin.
Gothmog	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>The Lord of Balrogs and High-captain of Angband, one of the foremost captains of the Dark Lord Morgoth during the First Age. He held command among Morgoth's most terrible servants and appeared in the great wars of Beleriand as a chief captain of the Balrogs. His name is associated with roots meaning dread and compulsion, force, subjection, or oppression.
Guilin	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A lord of Nargothrond, chief of one of the four kindreds within that realm, and considered among the most noble in name and lineage. Father of Gelmir and Gwindor, both renowned for valor, he and his folk were notable contributors to the building of the deep mansions of Nargothrond. They dwelt west of the city on the slopes of Taur-en-Faroth, the Hunters' Wold.
Gwindor	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Son of Guilin and brother of Gelmir, an Elf-lord of Nargothrond betrothed to Finduilas, daughter of King Orodreth. Reckoned as a bold leader and the scout who ranged farthest afield of all the folk of Nargothrond, he belonged to one of the noble houses of that realm. His story is closely connected with Finduilas, Túrin, and the counsels of Nargothrond in the First Age.
Idril	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Idril Celebrindal, only child of King Turgon of Gondolin and his Vanyarin wife Elenwë. Wife of Tuor and mother of Eärendil the Mariner, she was wise and far-seeing, with a heart often troubled by foreboding. Her union with Tuor was the second union of Elves and Men, after Beren and Lúthien, and through her the line of the Half-elven descended.
Ilmarë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>One of the chiefs of the Maiar and the handmaiden of Queen Varda. She is mentioned briefly in the Valaquenta alongside Eönwë, the banner-bearer and herald of King Manwë. Her name may be related to a Quenya word for starlight and to such words as Ilmen and Ilmarin.
Indis	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Vanyar">Vanyar</a><br><br>A Vanyarin Elf, close kin to Ingwë, King of the Vanyar, and the second wife of Finwë. She was renowned for swiftness of foot and skill at singing. With Finwë she had four children: Findis, Fingolfin, Írimë, and Finarfin. Indis did not go into exile, but abided among the Vanyar with Findis.
Ingwë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Vanyar">Vanyar</a><br><br>King of the Vanyar and High King of the Elves. One of the ambassadors who travelled with Oromë to the Blessed Realm, he became leader of the Vanyar during the Great March. The Vanyar first dwelt in Tirion with the Noldor, and Ingwë built the great white tower called Mindon Eldaliéva there. He later went to live on Taniquetil at the feet of Manwë.
Irmo|Lórien	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>A Vala known as the master of visions and dreams, more commonly called Lórien after his place of dwelling. He was the younger brother of Námo, and together they were known as the Fëanturi, the masters of spirits; their sister was Nienna. Irmo lived with his spouse Estë in the Gardens of Lórien west of Valimar, where he tended and gave refuge to the Elves of Valinor through visions and dreams. His name means Desirer or Master of Desire, while Lórien means Land of Dreams.
Lúthien	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>Lúthien Tinúviel, meaning Nightingale, was the fairest of all the Children of Ilúvatar. Only child of Elu Thingol, King of Doriath, and Melian the Maia, she was the sole offspring of the union between one of the Ainur and one of the Elves. Through her mother she possessed powers greater than any other of the Eldar, including gifts of enchantment and song. In the woods of Neldoreth she encountered Beren, a mortal Man of the House of Bëor, and their love became the first union of Elf and Man.
Mablung	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>An Elf of Doriath and the chief captain of King Thingol. He was counted among the leading warriors and hunters of Thingol's realm, and is associated in the histories with Beleg and the guarded borders of Doriath. His Sindarin name means with weighted hand, from mab meaning hand and lung meaning heavy; he is also called Mablung of the Heavy Hand, Mablung the Hunter, and Thingol's chief huntsman.
Maedhros	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Eldest of the seven sons of Fëanor and Nerdanel, and one of the chief princes of the Noldor. He was close to his cousin Fingon, whose friendship helped heal the breach between the Houses of Fingolfin and Fëanor. Maedhros later organized the Union of Maedhros, an effort to unite the peoples of Beleriand against Morgoth, and is remembered for leadership, endurance, and the burden of the Oath of Fëanor.
Maeglin	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Son of Eöl the Dark Elf and Aredhel, sister of Turgon. Born in Nan Elmoth, he came with his mother to Gondolin and became mighty among its people. Skilled in mining and smithcraft, he searched for ore in the mountains and held a notable place in the hidden city. His story is closely bound to the houses of Eöl, Aredhel, Turgon, and Idril.
Maglor	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>The second of the sons of Fëanor, known for poetry and singing. In Tirion he swore the Oath of Fëanor, and later composed the Noldolantë, the Fall of the Noldor, in memory of the sorrows connected with that oath. In Beleriand his ward was the open region between the arms of the Gelion River, which became known as Maglor's Gap.
Mahtan	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin Elf, skilled smith of Valinor, and father of Nerdanel, the wife of Fëanor. He learned the arts of metalwork and stonecraft under Aulë and was called an Aulendur, a Servant of Aulë. Mahtan was fond of copper, wore a copper circlet, and was known as Urundil, meaning Copper-lover. He taught Fëanor smithcraft, though he later regretted how that knowledge was used. Mahtan was also unusual among Elves for having a beard early in his second cycle of life.
Mandos|Námo	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Doomsman of the Valar, one of the Aratar. His true name is Námo, meaning Judge or Ordainer in Quenya, though he is more commonly called Mandos after his dwelling place. He pronounces judgment at the bidding of Manwë and is keeper of the Houses of the Dead. Numbered among the Fëanturi with his brother Irmo, he is husband to Vairë the Weaver, whose tapestries line the halls of his realm. He knows and remembers nearly all things that were and shall be, except those still lying in the freedom of Ilúvatar.
Manwë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>Manwë Súlimo, the Elder King, King of the Valar, and High King of Arda. Dearest to Eru and closest to his mind, he was appointed Ruler of Arda and vicegerent on Earth. His attributes are air, winds, and the birds, which serve him and bring news from the farthest and deepest places of the world. He dwells with Varda atop Taniquetil, the highest mountain of the world, and together they can see farther than all other eyes. Manwë is a kind and compassionate ruler, unconcerned with his own power, and bears a sapphire sceptre made for him by the Noldor.
Melian	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia who dwelt in the Gardens of Lórien in Valinor, tending its trees. Most beautiful, wise, and skilled in songs of enchantment among all the people of Irmo, she also served Vána and Estë. In Middle-earth she encountered Elwë of the Teleri in Nan Elmoth; they wed, and she became Queen of Doriath, the only known Ainu to take one of the Children of Ilúvatar as spouse. She bore Lúthien Tinúviel and shrouded Doriath in the Girdle of Melian, an invisible barrier of magic and mystery.
Melkor|Morgoth	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Ainur">Ainur</a><br><br>Greatest and most powerful of all the Ainur created by Eru Ilúvatar, though he fell from glory and was cast out from the company of the Valar. In the Music of the Ainur he wove discord into the Theme of Ilúvatar, and when he entered Arda he claimed mastery over it. His power at the beginning was greater than that of any other Vala, and he corrupted many Ainur to his service, marred Arda, and waged war against the Valar and the Children of Ilúvatar. He was later named Morgoth Bauglir, meaning Dark Enemy or Black Foe of the World.
Míriel	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Míriel Þerindë, also spelled Serindë, was the first wife of Finwë, King of the Noldor, and the mother of Fëanor. She was devoted to crafts, unsurpassed in weaving and needlework, and her mother-name means the Broideress in reference to her marvelous dexterity of hand. Her name may mean Jewel-daughter, and her hair was described as silver in appearance, an unusual colour for one of the Noldor.
Narvi	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Dwarves">Dwarves</a><br><br>A great Dwarven craftsman of Khazad-dûm during the height of its glory. He was renowned for his craft and formed a friendship with Celebrimbor, the Elf-lord and master artificer of neighbouring Eregion. Together they made the mighty Doors of Durin, which guarded the West-gate of the Dwarven city. Narvi stands as one of the few named Dwarven artisans closely associated with the shared craft of Khazad-dûm and Eregion.
Nerdanel	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Daughter of Mahtan the smith and wife of Fëanor. A skilled sculptor, she made statues so lifelike that people thought them real and tried to speak to them. Known as Nerdanel the Wise, she was strong-willed, free of mind, filled with desire for knowledge, and more patient than her husband. She bore Fëanor seven sons: Maedhros, Maglor, Celegorm, Caranthir, Curufin, Amrod, and Amras, an unusually large family among the Eldar.
Nessa	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>One of the Valier, sister of Oromë and wife of Tulkas. Lithe and fleet of foot, she is swift as an arrow and can outrun the deer who follow her in the wild. She is renowned for dancing upon the ever-green lawns of Valimar. Her name means young in Quenya, and she wed Tulkas upon the Isle of Almaren.
Nienna	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>A Queen of the Valar, sister of Mandos and Irmo, and one of the Aratar. She is acquainted with grief and sorrow, but also with pity and courage, and mourns for the wounds of the world caused by evil. Those who listen to her learn wisdom and endurance in grief. Nienna dwells alone in the distant west, close to the Halls of Mandos, and goes there often to comfort and counsel those in the Halls of Waiting. She wears a grey hood, and her name contains the Quenya word nie, meaning tear. Olórin learned much from her.
Nimloth	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>An Elf-maiden of Doriath, daughter of Galathil. She wedded Dior Eluchíl, heir of King Thingol, and for a time they dwelt by the waterfall of Lanthir Lamath at the base of the Blue Mountains. She bore three children: the twin sons Eluréd and Elurín, and a daughter, Elwing. Her Sindarin name means White Blossom.
Olwë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Teleri">Teleri</a><br><br>Lord of Alqualondë and king of the Teleri in Aman, also known as the Falmari. Younger brother of Elwë, who became Thingol of Doriath, he led the Teleri who completed the Great Journey to Valinor after his brother remained in Beleriand. He built Alqualondë, the greatest city of the Teleri on the shores of Aman, and was father of Eärwen, who wed Finarfin.
Olórin	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of Valinor, later known in Middle-earth as Gandalf. He was counted among the wisest of the Maiar and was associated with Manwë, Varda, Irmo, and Nienna. In his youth he dwelt in Lórien, and his ways often took him to the house of Nienna, from whom he learned pity and patience. In the Third Age he was sent to Middle-earth by the Valar as one of the Istari.
Orodreth	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Son of Angrod, lord of the Noldor, and a dynast of the House of Finarfin. He served as warden of Minas Tirith under his uncle Finrod and later became King of Nargothrond. Father of Finduilas and Gil-galad, he belongs to the royal lineage linking the House of Finarfin with the great hidden realm on the River Narog.
Oromë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Huntsman of the Valar and the Great Rider, one of the Aratar. He was a hunter of monsters and evil creatures, riding upon his steed Nahar and blowing his great horn Valaróma. Oromë loved horses, hounds, trees, and forests, and in Yavanna's woods in Valinor he trained his folk and beasts to hunt the evil creatures of Melkor. He was the brother of Nessa and husband of Vána, and was the first among the Valar to find the Elves at Cuiviénen. He gave them the name Eldar and accompanied them from Cuiviénen to Beleriand.
Ossë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of the Inner Seas associated with Ulmo, loving the winds and preferring the coasts and isles of Middle-earth to the deeps. He was the spouse of Uinen. During the early days of Arda, Ossë turned to Melkor for a time, but Uinen brought him back to loyalty to Ulmo. Some darkness and violence remained in his spirit, and he enjoyed raging in storms despite Ulmo's will, while only Uinen could restrain his wild urges. He befriended the Lindar during the Great March, taught them sea-lore and sea-music, and in the Second Age raised the island of Númenor from the depths.
Pallando	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia associated with Oromë and friend of Alatar, who took him along when chosen for the mission to Middle-earth as one of the Istari. The two were known as the Blue Wizards and journeyed into the far East and South of Middle-earth, where they were sent to contest the will of Sauron. Pallando is a Quenya name that may contain the element palan-, meaning far.
Pengolodh	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A loremaster of the Noldor, born in Nevrast to a Sindarin and a Noldorin parent, whose Sindarin name means teaching sage or doctor of lore. When Turgon built Gondolin, Pengolodh moved with the people there and became one of its great scholars. He was a member of the Lambengolmor and was known as the Sage of the Noldor, counted as the greatest loremaster since Fëanor and Rúmil. The Annals of Beleriand are attributed to him, as are the edited Annals of Valinor, furthering the work of Rúmil.
Penlod	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Gnome-lord of Gondolin in the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales. He was marshal of both the House of the Pillar and the House of the Tower of Snow, and was described as the tallest of the Gnomes. His name is Gnomish, though its meaning is not glossed; its Qenya cognate was Pendelot.
Rog	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Gnome-lord of Gondolin in the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales. Rog was a blacksmith and chief of the folk of the Hammer of Wrath. He was considered the strongest of the Noldoli and among the greatest in valour. His name appeared earlier as Rôg, while the early Gnomish Lexicon gives rog as doughty or strong; its Qenya form was Rōka.
Rúmil	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>A Noldorin sage of Tirion, one of the Lambengolmor, the Loremasters of the Noldor, and the first deviser of written characters among the Elves. In the days of bliss in Valinor, he invented a writing system fitting for recording speech and song, creating letters both for graving upon metal or stone and for drawing with brush or pen. His alphabet was called the Tengwar of Rúmil, or Sarati, meaning "letters," as each character was called a sarat. This system was later expanded and perfected by Fëanor into the Tengwar of Fëanor, more commonly known simply as Tengwar. Very learned in languages, he studied the secret tongue of the Valar through the teaching of Aulë. To him is attributed the authorship of the earliest annals and lore of the Elder Days, including accounts of the Ainulindalë and the early history of Arda. His chronicles preserved the oldest traditions of the creation of the world and the doings of the Valar and Eldar in the ancient days.
Saeros	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Nandor">Nandor</a><br><br>A counsellor at the court of King Thingol in Doriath, of the Guest-elves: Green-elves or Nandor who sought refuge in the hidden kingdom. His father Ithilbor was chief of the Guest-elves and held a permanent seat in Thingol's council. Proud and resentful, Saeros begrudged the honour and esteem that Thingol showed to Túrin, the human foster son of the king.
Salmar	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia who entered Arda with Ulmo. Salmar was the maker of the Ulumúri, the great horns of Ulmo, which produce the music of the sea. In the early version of the legendarium preserved in The Book of Lost Tales, Salmar was also called Noldorin and was counted as a Vala, but in the later account he is a Maia associated with Ulmo.
Sauron|Mairon	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia of Aulë the Smith, mightiest of that Vala's people, originally called Mairon, meaning The Admirable in Quenya. From Aulë he learned much of smithing and handiwork, becoming a great craftsman and mighty in lore. Coveting power through which he would coordinate all things according to his own will, he was ensnared by Melkor in the Spring of Arda and became his greatest and most trusted servant. By the time the Elves awoke, he had command over Angband as Melkor's lieutenant.
Thingol|Elwë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Sindar">Sindar</a><br><br>Originally called Elwë, one of the two leaders of the Teleri during the Great Journey from Cuiviénen, along with his younger brother Olwë. In Beleriand he encountered Melian, one of the Maiar, in the forest of Nan Elmoth, and alone among the Children of Ilúvatar he married one of the Ainur. Known thereafter as Elu Thingol in Sindarin, he became High King of the Sindar and founded Doriath. Father of Lúthien Tinúviel, he ruled a realm protected by Melian's power.
Thorin|Thorin Oakenshield	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Dwarves">Dwarves</a><br><br>Thorin II, called Thorin Oakenshield, was King of Durin's Folk, son of Thráin II, grandson of Thrór, and elder brother of Frerin and Dís. After the dragon Smaug drove the Dwarves of Erebor into exile, Thorin lived among Durin's Folk in the Blue Mountains and became their leader. His epithet Oakenshield came from the Battle of Azanulbizar, where he used a branch of oak as a shield after his own was broken. In T.A. 2941 he led the Quest of Erebor with twelve Dwarves, Bilbo Baggins, and Gandalf, seeking the recovery of the Lonely Mountain. He was a proud and formidable Dwarf-lord, associated with the heirlooms and hopes of the House of Durin.
Tilion	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>A Maia who guided the Moon. In the days of the Trees in Valinor, Tilion was a hunter from the company of Oromë and often rode with him, though he spent much of his free time in Lórien under the light of Telperion. He loved silver, used a silver bow, and begged to be given the care of the Moon. He was less mighty than Arien, the Maia chosen to guide the Sun, and was drawn by her splendour; reckless at times, he did not always follow the correct path.
Tulkas	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>A Vala, the most warlike of the Valar and the spouse of Nessa. Tulkas was so strong and quick that he needed neither weapon nor steed, and he delighted in deeds of prowess and strength such as wrestling and fighting. His flesh was ruddy, his hair and beard golden, and his laughter was loud in sport and war. He came to Arda after the other Valar had begun their struggle with Melkor, and his arrival helped bring about the Spring of Arda. A hardy friend, he was slow to wrath but also slow to forgive, quick in action, and not good in counsel.
Turgon	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Second son of Fingolfin, younger brother of Fingon and elder brother of Aredhel and Argon. In Aman he married Elenwë of the Vanyar, and they had a daughter, Idril Celebrindal. Guided by visions from Ulmo, he discovered the hidden valley of Tumladen and there founded Gondolin, the Hidden City, building it in secret over many years. The city was concealed by the Encircling Mountains and guarded by the Eagles of Thorondor, making Turgon one of the great hidden rulers of the Noldor.
Uinen	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Maiar">Maiar</a><br><br>Lady of the Seas, a Maia of Ulmo and spouse of Ossë. She loved and protected all creatures and weeds that live in the sea, brought calm seas, and could calm the tumultuous waves of her husband; for this she was loved by mariners. It was said that her hair spread through all the surface of water. Early in the history of Arda, after Ossë was corrupted by Morgoth, Aulë pleaded with Uinen to persuade him to return to the service of Ulmo.
Ulmo	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>Lord of Waters, King of the Sea, and Dweller of the Deep, one of the Aratar and third in majesty after Manwë and Varda. All waters are under his government, from the great ocean Ekkaia to bays and rivers and even the waters under the earth. His spirit runs in the very veins of the world, and he dwells not in Valinor but in the deeps of the seas around and below Ambar. Of all the Ainur he was most deeply instructed in music; he speaks through the sound of water and makes music through his great horns, the Ulumúri. When he appears, he is dreadful and terrible as a mounting wave that strides to the land, clad in shimmering silver-green mail and wearing a dark foam-crested helm, with a voice deep like the ocean. He cared for Arda and the Children of Eru, and alone of the Valar never forsook them.
Vairë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Weaver, one of the Valier and the wife of Mandos. She is responsible for weaving the story of the World, with which the Halls of Mandos are clothed and ever widen. Her work gives her a quiet but profound place among the Powers, preserving the memory of Arda in woven form. Her Quenya name means Weaver or Ever-weaving, derived from the root WIR; in The Etymologies it is connected with a root meaning wind or weave.
Varda|Elbereth	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>Queen of the Valar and Lady of the Stars, one of the Aratar. Wife of Manwë and mightiest of the Valier, dwelling with him upon Taniquetil. Called Elbereth Gilthoniel by the Elves in Sindarin, and Elentári, Star-Queen, in Quenya. Too great is her beauty to be declared in words of Men or Elves, for the light of Ilúvatar lives still in her face, and in light is her power and her joy. Knows all the regions of Eä and rejoices in light. Filled the Two Lamps with radiance during the Spring of Arda. Before the awakening of the Elves, she undertook her greatest work: taking the dew from the vats of Telperion, she created new and brighter stars, setting many individual stars and also constellations, including Carnil, Luinil, Nénar, Lumbar, Alcarinquë, Elemmírë, and the Sickle of the Valar. Together with Manwë she sees beyond all eyes through mist and darkness, and with him hears all voices from every corner of the world. In Middle-earth she is most revered by the Elves, who call upon her name and sing hymns to her. The very mention of her name is said to be deadly to evil spirits. Her name Varda means "Sublime," "Exalted," or "Lofty" in Quenya.
Voronwë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Voronwë Aranwion, called the Steadfast, was a mariner of Gondolin and son of Aranwë, a nobleman related to the House of Fingolfin. His mother was one of the Sindar of the Falas, descended from the people of Círdan, giving him both Noldorin and Sindarin heritage. Connected with the will of Ulmo, he became a guide to Tuor through the wastes and perils of Beleriand toward the hidden entrance of Gondolin.
Vána	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Ever-young, one of the Valier. Younger sister of Yavanna and spouse of Oromë. Possesses influence over the flora and fauna of Middle-earth. All flowers spring as she passes and open if she glances upon them, and all birds sing at her coming. Dwells in gardens filled with golden flowers, and often comes to the forests of Oromë. The Maia Arien tended the golden flowers of her gardens, watering them with the bright dews from Laurelin in the days of the Two Trees. Melian also served Vána and Estë before departing to Middle-earth. Her name means "beautiful" in Quenya, related to unmarred beauty.
Yavanna|Kementári	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Valar">Valar</a><br><br>The Giver of Fruits and Queen of the Earth, one of the Aratar. Called Kementári, meaning Queen of the Earth. Elder sister of Vána and spouse of Aulë, with whom she dwells in central Valinor. Lover of all things that grow in the earth, holding countless forms in her mind, from the trees like towers in forests long ago to the moss upon stones and the small secret things in the mould. All growing things answer to her, both the olvar that are rooted in place and the kelvar that move freely. In reverence she is next to Varda among the Queens of the Valar. Her usual form is that of a tall woman robed in green, though at times she takes other shapes. Some have seen her standing like a tree under heaven, crowned with the Sun and with roots plunging into the waters beneath. From her thoughts came the shapes of the Two Trees of Valinor, Telperion and Laurelin. At her request, Eru gave life to the Ents as shepherds of the trees. Her name means "Giver of Fruits" in Quenya.
Írimë	<i>Race:</i> <a href="bword://Noldor">Noldor</a><br><br>Third child and second daughter of Finwë and his second wife Indis of the Vanyar. Sister to Findis, Fingolfin, and Finarfin, and half-sister to Fëanor. Known more commonly by her mother-name Lalwendë, or in shortened form Lalwen, she was particularly close to her brother Fingolfin. Her name Írimë is Quenya, likely a feminine form of írima, meaning desirable or lovely, and her story belongs to Tolkien's later accounts of the House of Finwë.
